##It took me 19 days to get back to school in Australia

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Contributing writer, the paper, Wang Weihuan

My name is Weihuan Wang and I am studying information technology at the University of Tasmania in Australia. Our school opened on February 24, but my plans to return to Australia were derailed by the COVID-19 outbreak.

At the beginning of the epidemic, I was optimistic. I only moved up my ticket from February 17 to February 12, and flew back to Australia from Hangzhou. However, on February 1, our lives of overseas students changed dramatically.

Australian Prime Minister Morrison has issued an emergency travel ban in response to the new coronavirus outbreak: from February 1, people who have spent the past 14 days in mainland China will not be allowed to enter Australia, except Australians, permanent residents and their immediate family members.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On 1 February, the Australian government issued an emergency travel ban

The February 1 ban has almost exploded the circle of Friends of Australian students abroad, with everyone half joking that they might not be able to go back to school, and some even joking about their brothers who are now on a flight to Australia, it's GonNa be a tough one going through customs.

Then came a series of flight cancellations, and everywhere I looked in the circle of friends, there was a lot of wailing, and everyone's flights, including mine, were canceled because of the ban. Who would have thought that after 20 years of study, I would graduate in my last year and face the crisis of "dropping out of school" .

I got a cancellation notice

01
A ray of life

01

A ray of life

As for the February 1 ban, speculation is rife that if you stay in a third country for 14 days before flying to Australia, you will be able to get in?

A few days later, the Australian government issued an accompanying note: "can accept students to transfer to a third country for 14 days to enter Australia. "

At midnight on February 6th, after much agonizing, I finally bought a plane ticket to Bangkok the next night. I didn't even know what I needed to land the ticket. Thailand was a wild card for me. When I told my parents the next morning, it was clear that they were a little confused. I just felt that time was running out and I had to go. By the way, I fixed the date for 14 days and bought a ticket for bangkok-brunei-melbourne flight.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
According to Australian Department of Education Data in 2019, Chinese students accounted for about a quarter of the total number of Australian students studying abroad

On Feb. 7, after a rush to clean up, I even had a blood test and a chest CT, and after making sure I was okay, my parents drove me to the airport.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Pre-trip checklist

At 8 pm, the Xiaoshan Airport was deserted, deserted like an abandoned building, with only a few people left, leaving the "international departure" to my departure on lion air. Later, I heard from my Thai friend on the same flight that this was the penultimate flight of Lion Air Thailand's hangzhou-bangkok route. If I had hesitated a little, I might not be able to go to Thailand.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Xiaoshan airport on a rainy night

After arriving in Bangkok and exiting the airport at 5 a.m. on Feb. 8, he picked up his luggage and went to buy a phone card, only to find his passport was missing. After a fruitless search, I went to the police station and found my passport safely in the secret pocket of my camera bag. After a false alarm, finally returned to the hotel to rest.

After arriving at the hotel, I fell asleep on the bed, unable to resist the drowsiness of the journey. February 8 is the Lantern Festival of the Chinese Lunar New Year. The first full moon of the New Year drives away the tedium of the long cold winter, but no dumplings.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
In Chiang Mai

The day after arriving in Bangkok, I left for Chiang Mai, with four friends waiting for me in Chiang Mai, who also had to make a 14-day stopover in a third country. The weather in Chiang Mai is much better than Bangkok. It's not as wet as Bangkok. What's more, I am happy to join my friends.

We played in Chiang Mai for 10 days or so, where consumption is cheap, feel every day to eat and drink, do massage chicken, a day passed, every day is happy. After a year of animation in 2018 and a year of IT in 2019, IT was a rare holiday for me to relax.

However, the news about Australia has been spotty, with friends and family sending out occasional greetings. There were also rumours online that the failure to call the Australian immigration service could lead to the cancellation of student visas. At that time, I felt that the students who were waiting to return to Australia in a third country were very nervous and easily frightened.
All the fake news on the Internet made me feel at times like I had a chance to go back to Australia, and at other times I was terrified that my visa would be cancelled.

02
Midnight Thunderbolt

02

Midnight Thunderbolt

My friends bought a non-stop flight from Thailand to Melbourne, while I bought a flight from Bangkok on February 22 on Brunei to Melbourne. I'm going back to Bangkok from Chiang Mai on the 21st.

The night before I returned to Bangkok, my friend sent a screenshot of a flight that had been blocked by an outbreak on Brunei Airlines, which had people from Zhejiang and Jiangsu on board, and was so severely restricted that it was impossible to get a connecting flight.

By then, it was 12 p.m. , the airline's customer service was closed, and I had to search through groups of international students in third countries. Then another question was raised. The Australian government issued a document saying that if a student who had been in a third country for 14 days was admitted, would the date of arrival count as one day? Or does it start after that time?

Different interpretations of documents by airlines and different algorithms by Australian Customs could lead to visa cancellations. There are two dominant online terms, one is n + 14 and the other is n + 15(N is the date of entry into a third country) .

In my case, I entered Thailand on February 8, leaving on the 22nd is n + 14 days, and Thailand has only 14 days on arrival, so the 22nd is the last day of visa validity. But N + 14 would be denied boarding by many airlines, and N + 15 would be allowed to board. But if I leave the country on February 23rd according to n + 15, the Thai visa will expire on arrival.

In the midst of all this, I had my first sleeplessness in Thailand.

I probably woke up after only 3 hours of sleep. The first call I made was to Brunei Airlines. The staff told me that people in Zhejiang definitely couldn't fly, but she suggested we wait and see. After all, policies change every day.

I do not think the next day will be the Zhejiang people lift the ban, so bought the flight 23 on the spot. This cool air ticket from bangkok-singapore-melbourne on the 23rd saved me, but it was also the beginning of a difficult journey behind me.

03
A bumpy ride home

03

A bumpy ride home

When we arrived at the Don Mueang International Airport, it was still early to check out. The check-in clerk held my passport for a while, then asked me whether I prefer a window or a corridor, and printed out the boarding pass for me, "You have been abroad for 15 days, and according to the regulations you can go back to Australia. ".

The heart of the stone finally fell.

As I was going through customs, the officer looked at my passport and silently pointed to a counter in the back.

PA, a chapter down, in Thailand within 24 hours, the police did not fine, let me go, closer and closer to returning to Australia!

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Thai customs stamp expired but cleared

I was on the 4:00 pm flight when I got lost and fell asleep in the departure lounge. When I woke up, it was 4:10, and then I heard the airport announcement, and the flight was delayed.

After a while, the radio said the gate had been changed, and the flight was delayed until 6:00. I changed the gate, but as the hour approached 6 o'clock, there was a long line, and suddenly an Indian guy came out in front of me and said, "the flight is cancelled. ".

That's what you get for waiting all afternoon?

At this time, some Chinese students who were also going to Australia came to accost us. Most of them were going to Melbourne and Sydney. Now the flight to Singapore has been cancelled. They put their passports together and are ready to go in groups.

The airline gave us four options, the first three were at Suvarnabhumi Airport, and there was an 8:00 flight to Singapore. The last option is to stay at Don Muang Airport, although there is no flight to Singapore until 11 pm.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Several solutions offered by airlines

Our flights from Singapore to Melbourne and Sydney are at 0.40 am and 2.00 am respectively. If we stay at Don Muang, we won't be able to catch the next flight. Only the 8:00 pm Suvarnabhumi Airport flight to Singapore, and we're just in time for the next flight. But we'd have to go back through customs, get our bags, and then take an airline bus from Don Muang Airport, north of Bangkok, to the East Suvarnabhumi Airport. It was 6:30 p.m. , at least an hour to Suvarnabhumi.

There was a long queue out of the customs. As the queue advanced slowly, two Chinese students in front of us were stopped by the customs. We asked about the two Chinese students who were refused entry by Thai customs because they had overstayed their stay.

Like the Chinese students, we couldn't go through customs again, so we couldn't take the bus to Suvarnabhumi Airport and catch the only flight that would take us anywhere. So we went back to the gate and waited for the 11 p.m. Flight from Don Muang Airport, when everyone was hungry and sure to miss the flight back to Melbourne and Sydney.

The bad news, however, is not over.

Since we couldn't get into Singapore, the only way to get us back to Australia was on a full coolair flight. But the first available Kuhang flights to Melbourne and Sydney were February 25 and 26, respectively, the day we left Bangkok on February 23.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Waiting in the departure lounge

So we boarded the 11 p.m. flight to Singapore Changi Airport with an unknown, weary, and unquenchable longing.

04
And then it turns around

04

And then it turns around

Arriving in Singapore, it was 2:40 a.m. , and the airport was almost empty as people dragged their tired bodies off the plane. But after a series of twists and turns, finally there is good news, the airline agreed to transfer us to Singapore Airlines flight back to Australia!

We, a group of international students trapped at Singapore's airport, set off for another terminal as if we were middle school students on a spring outing to get our boarding passes.

By the time I got my boarding pass, it was 4:30 a.m. Some of the friends are chatting together, some have slept on the Sofa, and some are playing with their mobile phones. I'm starving. I'm just looking for a place to eat.

My friends were on an early flight to Sydney, leaving for the gate at about 6:00, and I watched them leave as we said goodbye. After 12 hours of uncertainty, is everyone's life back on track?

Next, our flight check-in for Melbourne is about to begin. It is obvious that the flow of people has increased along the way. The Singapore Airport at 7 am began to be lively and bustling with people passing through, but not many people wear masks, and it doesn't seem to bother anyone.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Finally got on a flight back to Australia

When the staff said "welcome aboard, " I was so excited, it was the second to last level!

I was so tired after a long night that I slept the last two hours of the eight hour flight. It was a little after 4:00 pm when we arrived in Melbourne, and it had already taken more than a day to get going.

The last hurdle was when I went through the customs. The customs guy took my passport, checked my date, and chatted with me about my trip to Thailand. He thought that the overseas students had had to go through a lot of trouble to get back to Australia. And he said, "are you going back to Hobart today? "

"No, I'm too tired. Today I just want to sleep. Tomorrow I'll go back to Hobart. " .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A queue of people at Australian Customs

It took me 19 days from February 7th to February 25th to return to the Tasmania, an island at the end of the world, Florida, just south of the South Pole.

Last words

That's pretty much the end of the story, but I'd like to add a few points:

1. The day after I returned to Hobart, the school sent me an e mail and called me. The staff was very concerned about the mental health of our students who had been in a third country for 14 days. After all, they might be discriminated against if they returned to Australia, tell us to talk to them if we have any problems, and hope that when I get back to Tas, my life will be back to normal, no psychological burden.

2. The car radio host keeps asking locals to go to Chinese restaurants because the outbreak has left many restaurants struggling and even closing, urging them to help their Chinese friends.

3. The University of Tasmania is an earlier grant for schools, a 1,500 Australian dollar (6,900 yuan) travel grant for students who transit to a third country, and a 500 Australian dollar Internet subsidy for students who are stranded in China, there are also many online lectures and online tutorials, and teachers are especially concerned about the plight of students stranded in China. They have even set up wechat groups to help students answer questions.

This trip is all the way by national policies run, in the policy of the slit in the survival. Every country has taken various preventive measures and actions in response to the epidemic, and policies are changing all the time. Everyone bears the possibility of change. Third countries are not the 100% path to success.

But at least I was lucky.
